## Vercel Web Analytics Installation

Successfully installed and configured Vercel Web Analytics for this Next.js project.

### Changes Made:

**1. Package Installation:**
- Installed `@vercel/analytics` version 2.0.1
- Updated package.json to include the new dependency
- Updated package-lock.json with resolved dependencies

**2. Analytics Integration:**
- Modified `src/app/layout.tsx` to integrate the Analytics component
- Added import statement: `import { Analytics } from '@vercel/analytics/next'`
- Added `<Analytics />` component inside the `<body>` tag, after the main application content

**3. Implementation Details:**
- Followed the official Vercel documentation for Next.js App Router
- The Analytics component is placed at the root layout level to track all pages
- Positioned after the main application content (AuthProvider and RootLayoutShell) to ensure it doesn't interfere with app functionality
- No additional configuration required - the component will automatically track page views when deployed to Vercel

### Framework-Specific Notes:

This is a Next.js 16.2.10 project using the App Router architecture. The Analytics component has been integrated according to the latest official Vercel documentation (fetched from https://vercel.com/docs/analytics/quickstart on July 12, 2026).

### Verification:

- ✅ Package installed successfully
- ✅ No linting errors introduced in modified files
- ✅ Code follows existing project patterns and conventions
- ✅ Analytics component properly imported and added to the root layout

### Next Steps:

To enable analytics tracking:
1. Deploy the project to Vercel
2. Navigate to the Analytics section in your Vercel dashboard
3. Click the "Enable" button to activate Web Analytics
4. After deployment, verify tracking by checking the browser's Network tab for a request to `/<unique-path>/view`

The analytics will automatically start tracking page views once enabled in the Vercel dashboard.
